ut 1300":"omkring 1300","before 24 August 1313":"før 24. august 1313","1339":"1339","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1272–before 24 August 1313":"circa 1272–vóór 24 augustus 1313","1272–1313":"1272–1313","–Male":"Overleden","1300–1339":"1300–1339","1225–1291":"1225–1291","1254–1313":"1254–1313","about 1272":"circa 1272","after 1291":"na 1291","before 12 November 1272":"vóór 12 november 1272","1272":"1272","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1313":"1313","1225":"1225","1300":"1300","1254":"1254","about 1300":"circa 1300","before 24 August 1313":"vóór 24 augustus 1313","1339":"1339","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1272–before 24 August 1313":"about 1272–before 24 August 1313","1272–1313":"1272–1313","–Male":"Deceased","1300–1339":"1300–1339","1225–1291":"1225–1291","1254–1313":"1254–1313","about 1272":"about 1272","after 1291":"after 1291","before 12 November 1272":"before 12 November 1272","1272":"1272","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1313":"1313","1225":"1225","1300":"1300","1254":"1254","about 1300":"about 1300","before 24 August 1313":"before 24 August 1313","1339":"1339","South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England":"South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hansard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Ansard</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>; from ancient Germanic <i>ans-</i> ‘(pagan) god’ + <i>ward</i> ‘guard, protector’ or <i>hard-</i> ‘brave, hardy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hazard","meanings":["English: Anglo-Norman French variant of   Hansard  .","English and French: nickname from Old French, Middle English <i>hasard</i>, <i>hazard</i> ‘game of dice’, perhaps given to a player at hazard, i.e. a gambler, trickster, or rascal. The word probably derives from Arabic <i>az-zahr</i>, from <i>az</i>, assimilated form of the definite article <i>al</i>, + <i>zahr</i> ‘die’. It appears to have been picked up in the Holy Land and brought back to Europe by Provençal crusaders.","English: possibly in some instances of Flemish origin, a nickname from Middle Dutch <i>hasart</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":18,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Hansard was born about 1272, in South Kelsey, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Sir Gilbert Hansard III, was 49 and his mother, Joan de Columbers, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Redman. He died before 24 August 1313, in Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"about 1272–befo